+# FreelanceEscrow
+
+A USDC escrow for freelance jobs. The client funds a job, the freelancer delivers,
+the client accepts, and the contract pays out. If the client goes quiet, the
+freelancer gets paid anyway. If they disagree, a named arbiter splits the money.
+
+Foundry project. Contract in `src/FreelanceEscrow.sol`, 24 tests in `test/`.
+
+## How it works
+
+```
+createJob()  ──> Funded ──deliver()──> Delivered ──approve()────────> paid
+                   │                       │      └─claimExpired()──> paid
+                   ├─reclaim()  (delivery deadline passed)──────────> refunded
+                   ├─cancel()   (freelancer walks away)─────────────> refunded
+                   └─────dispute()─────────┴──> Disputed ─resolve()─> split
+```
+
+- **`createJob(freelancer, arbiter, amount, deliveryDeadline, reviewPeriod)`** — client
+  pulls USDC into escrow. Arbiter is optional; pass `address(0)` to disable disputes.
+- **`deliver(jobId)`** — freelancer starts the client's review window (1–30 days).
+- **`approve(jobId)`** — client accepts, freelancer is paid.
+- **`claimExpired(jobId)`** — freelancer is paid because the client let the review
+  window lapse. This is what stops a client from freezing funds by ignoring the job.
+- **`reclaim(jobId)`** — client is refunded because nothing was delivered by the deadline.
+- **`cancel(jobId)`** — freelancer refunds the client and walks away.
+- **`dispute(jobId)` / `resolve(jobId, toFreelancer)`** — either party escalates before
+  the review window ends; the arbiter awards any split of the escrowed amount.
+
+Two things worth knowing about the money. The fee is snapshotted per job at creation,
+so raising the platform fee later cannot change the payout of a job already funded.
+Fees accrue inside the contract and are withdrawn separately, so a failing fee transfer
+can never block a freelancer's payout.
+
+## Where to deploy it, and why
+
+**Deploy to Ethereum mainnet.** Then add Base later if your users turn out to live there.
+
+The usual argument for an L2 is gas, and at these job sizes that argument does not hold.
+Measured against live mainnet gas today, the full lifecycle of one job — token approval,
+`createJob`, `deliver`, `approve` — costs about **6 cents**. On a $10,000 job that is
+0.0006% of the amount. Stripe takes 2.9%. Upwork takes 10%. Gas is not your cost problem.
+
+What you are actually choosing is where $2,000–$50,000 of someone else's money sits for
+weeks at a time:
+
+- **Mainnet has no sequencer and no bridge.** Funds are in your contract, full stop. On
+  Base or Arbitrum they also depend on an upgradeable rollup contract controlled by a
+  security council, a sequencer that can stall, and a 7-day withdrawal path when you want
+  the money back on L1. That is a fine trade for a $5 game item. It is a harder
+  conversation with a client who wired you $50,000.
+- **USDC is native on mainnet.** Circle mints and redeems there. A business paying by wire
+  and a freelancer offramping to a bank both touch mainnet with the fewest hops.
+- **Trust is the product.** "The money is held on Ethereum" is a sentence a non-crypto
+  freelancer already half-understands. "Held on an optimistic rollup" is a support ticket.
+
+**Pick Base instead if** your users are consumer-side and already onboard through Coinbase
+— its onramp deposits straight to Base, which removes a bridging step that will cost you
+more signups than gas ever costs you dollars. Base also wins if you later add per-milestone
+releases or many small jobs, where the transaction count actually multiplies.
+
+Whatever you pick, run it on **Base Sepolia** first — same code, free, and the faucet USDC
+lets you walk the whole dispute flow end to end.
+
+### Measured costs
+
+Gas figures are from this repo's gas report and live `cast estimate` calls
+(2026-07-24, ETH $1,870, mainnet base fee 0.07–0.12 gwei, Base 0.006 gwei,
+Arbitrum 0.02 gwei). Gas moves — re-check with `cast base-fee`.
+
+| | Gas | Mainnet @0.1 gwei | Mainnet @1 gwei (busy) | Base | Arbitrum |
+|---|---|---|---|---|---|
+| Deploy contract | 2,174,832 | **$0.41** | $4.07 | $0.02 | $0.08 |
+| `createJob` | 143,807 | $0.027 | $0.27 | $0.0016 | $0.005 |
+| `deliver` | 33,601 | $0.006 | $0.06 | $0.0004 | $0.001 |
+| `approve` (release) | 94,039 | $0.018 | $0.18 | $0.0011 | $0.004 |
+| `resolve` (dispute) | 105,969 | $0.020 | $0.20 | $0.0012 | $0.004 |
+| **One full job** | 317,447 | **$0.06** | $0.59 | $0.004 | $0.012 |
+
+A one-time deploy under a dollar and 6 cents per job. Budget for gas spikes, not for gas.
+
+## Deploy it
+
+```bash
+cp .env.example .env     # fill in ETHERSCAN_API_KEY, OWNER
+forge test               # 24 tests
+```
+
+Testnet first:
+
+```bash
+forge script script/Deploy.s.sol:Deploy \
+  --rpc-url base_sepolia --broadcast --verify \
+  --account deployer
+```
+
+Mainnet:
+
+```bash
+forge script script/Deploy.s.sol:Deploy \
+  --rpc-url mainnet --broadcast --verify \
+  --account deployer
+```
+
+The script picks the canonical USDC for whichever chain you point it at (mainnet, Base,
+Arbitrum, Optimism, Sepolia, Base Sepolia). Set `TOKEN` to override, `FEE_BPS` for the
+platform fee in basis points (default 100 = 1%, hard cap 500), and `OWNER` for the fee
+recipient.
+
+Use a hardware wallet or an encrypted keystore, never a raw private key in `.env`:
+
+```bash
+cast wallet import deployer --interactive   # creates the --account referenced above
+```
+
+Then hand ownership to a multisig:
+
+```bash
+cast send $ESCROW "transferOwnership(address)" $SAFE --rpc-url mainnet --account deployer
+# the Safe then calls acceptOwnership()
+```
+
+## Before you take real money
+
+1. **Get it audited.** This is unaudited code holding $50,000 per job. Everything below
+   matters less than this.
+2. **Make the arbiter a multisig,** not a hot key on your server. The arbiter can move the
+   full escrowed amount on a disputed job.
+3. **Decide your defaults in the UI** — a 7-day review window and a delivery deadline
+   matched to the contract length are sane starting points. The contract only enforces
+   1–30 days for review and a 365-day cap on delivery.
+4. **USDC can freeze addresses.** If Circle blocklists a freelancer, `approve` reverts and
+   the funds stay put. The client can `dispute` and have the arbiter return the money.
+5. **Index the events.** `JobCreated`, `Delivered`, `Released`, `Refunded`, `Disputed`,
+   `Resolved` carry everything a dashboard needs — no contract reads required.
+
+## Scope
+
+Single payment per job, no milestones. No partial releases outside a dispute. No
+on-chain job metadata; keep briefs and deliverables off-chain and reference the `jobId`.
+Adding milestones means an array of amounts per job and a `releaseMilestone(jobId, i)` —
+that is the natural next version, and the transaction count it adds is the strongest
+argument for putting v2 on Base.
